In miktex a package like e.g. hyperref.tar.lzma can be used and
installed by various miktex version so it takes up space only once.
Version specific are only a rather small number of packages/files
like binaries and the two database packages (like
miktex-zzdb2-2.8.tar.lzma). 

As the packing methods changed (from cab to bz to lzma) older
versions of the package manager continuously loosed the capability
to install some packages when these were updated and then used a
newer archive type. And after some time Christian actively removes
support for older miktex version so that they no longer can install
with the package manager.

So the transition between versions is smooth: They are always 2-3
miktex versions which still "works". I personally like it. I never
update all my PCs on the same time: if something doesn't work I want
a fallback. 

  
